name: N-(Methylcarbamoyl)acetamid
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-4392
Reason:
The compound N-(Methylcarbamoyl)acetamide has several functional groups that influence its melting point. Starting with acetamide as the base structure, which has a melting point around 82°C, we consider the following effects: 
- The introduction of the N-Methylcarbamoyl group (-NHCOCH3): This introduces additional hydrogen bonding capability and steric bulk, which typically increases the melting point. Estimating this contribution as approximately +40°C due to the enhanced hydrogen bonding network and increased rigidity of the molecule. 
- The second amide group (NC(=O)-): Amide groups are strong hydrogen bond donors and acceptors, leading to a significant increase in melting point due to the intermolecular hydrogen bonding. This could contribute an additional +40°C. 
- The substitution on the nitrogen of the N-Methylcarbamoyl group adds steric hindrance and a slight inductive effect, which can raise the melting point. Since this effect is generally smaller than the ones mentioned previously, we can estimate this contribution to be around +10°C. 
- The presence of two carbonyls in close proximity can also lead to strong dipole-dipole interactions, as well as potential intramolecular hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point. This effect is not easy to quantify, but given the substantial impact on rigidifying the structure, we can estimate it at around +20°C. 
Combining all these effects, we add up the individual contributions to the base value of acetamide to predict the melting point of N-(Methylcarbamoyl)acetamide.
Prediction: 82 (base value for acetamide) + 40 (N-Methylcarbamoyl group) + 40 (additional amide group) + 10 (substitution on nitrogen) + 20 (proximity of two carbonyls) = 192°C
